Barack Obama is the fourth President of the United States to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama is coming to Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma as well as the medal and a check of over $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the metropolis of northern Sweden and will be busy all the time.
He first visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its climax with the ceremony, at which Obama takes over the prestigious prize.
He is the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he takes over the prize.
The president does not want to evade this issue because he knows that he is taking over the award as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He has stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the goal medal, the diploma and the check of over ten million Swedish kronor (about 24 million Czech kronor).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event programme will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, with the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests in addition to Norway’s King and Queen.
Obama was very cautious about the price from the start.
For example, he stated that he felt that he did not fully deserve the prize.
He also reiterated several times that the price is not only for him, but for all who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that for him this is a "call to action".
