Czech discovery: a substance that also works in 'steeled' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not act as strongly on common virus variants as one of the existing drugs.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured.
However, the drug composition can prolong the life of the patient and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a whole series of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus proliferation also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no drugs are more effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical and Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way for dealing with virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, scientists arrive at new "improved" compounds, which were prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Homeopathic and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the cleavage of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would form.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the multiplication of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper, published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further altered.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against the HIV protease was tested in the test tube, also against their resistant (resistant) variants, which were obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as with the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants, against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formations, makes the metallocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Akgenetik, Head of the Institute of Biochemistry and Chemistry of the Laboratory for Organic Biology.
