Is Islam French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted for a construction ban on minarets and concerns about Europe’s alleged Islamization are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a thorough and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe’s declared most secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely argumentative study of a dispute that the country has shared and appreciated over a decade and a half.
Bowen’s latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it, “Islamic Free Spaces.”
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students about the issues that most worries them.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and the rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-oriented banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane affairs, he argues, that make up everyday life, quite unlike the political dramas that the media occupy.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them by a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss-born Arab-Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
They don’t have all the arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who interviewed Bowen are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts – advocates of purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia – who now show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism may be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) really feel committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn had to make their historical compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognizes a "sharpening of the value screws" rather than a growing pragmatism.
After reading this book, one is inclined to say "yes, but not yet".
