The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatically than any other environmental region on Earth.
The ice that marks it melts at alarming speed and takes life that can’t survive anywhere else.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests have entered the newly open waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now also authors in their keel waters.
Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws in "On Thin Ice" (original title: "On Thin Ice") a natural history of the icon of the North, the polar bear.
Wandering through the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who have proven themselves in hunting polar bears.
Admiral Nelson's encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old wingman at sea, who fought only with the rifle of his musket, is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were brought to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears in a performance.
Even today, zoos typically still own a millionth of the habitat of a wild old animal. The climate is rarely suitable: The polar bear in Singapore has become quite green by the algae growing in the hollow hairs of its fur.
