Ellis refers to the reports of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, landing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and motor sled-driven Inuit use powerful storm rifles to bring their prey to the range.
Ironically, ice will last the longest in the waters in the north of these two hunting nations.
In his new book “After the Ice,” Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine “New Scientist,” offers a clear and disturbing description of Arctic science and a compelling insight into how the future could evolve.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of changes.
However, this is not due to a lack of explanations.
The pioneering journeys of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and early 20th centuries gave the impression for the first time of the turmoil of the Packeis.
In the Cold War, submarines assumed the shifting ridges as they submerged.
A useful addition are satellite measurements and the large-scale deployment of measurement probes on icebergs, but much is still being achieved by fearless people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the peculiar, tiny world of the inflow system within the Arctic ice, formed by saltwater streams that are compressed as they freeze.
But, ranging from the bear on the ice to the microscopic wonders in the ice, everyone is threatened once the summer ice passes, which is expected between 2013 and 2050.
