Marines were among the 6,000 who deployed wreaths in Arlington
De'Angello Robinson traveled seven hours by bus to put a single wreath on the grave of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other Marines who made the journey from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina, to the National Cemetery in Arlington to decorate graves, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they have stepped.
In a few months, wherever we are brought back from, we could be," Robinson said of the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I wish someone would do the same for me, so I try to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who had gathered on Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of the mourning wreath manufacturer Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992 when he and some others decided to decorate several hundred graves at the cemetery in Arlington.
It is now an 18-year-old tradition and Morrill and his wife Karen, who make this trip every year, stop in different cities along the way to conduct events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, which expanded the event to other states.
This year, volunteers placed more than 16,000 crowns on the graves at Arlington Cemetery, in areas at the Pentagon, on graves at Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at the memorial site for United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsyl.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 to purchase and transport the wreaths.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way of giving something back to those victims.
She said this is a small contribution to how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It’s like visiting a family cemetery.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers wandered across the extensive lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers had older graves from the First and Second World Wars and the Vietnam War as their target, as these are not visited as often as the newer graves, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children were playing and couples were holding hands while carrying the fresh pine branches to the grayish gravestones.
Each round wreath was dark green with a small red loop attached to the top.
Section 60, which is located nearby and where mostly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost quiet.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 crowns to decorate this section, but the grim mood of the current wars filled this area.
Individuals wept openly, others prayed, and families and friends clung to each other in the icy air.
Some read the names carved in stone, while others bowed down to small black-and-white square cards that had been stuck in the wet mud for those whose tombstones had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of many mothers who shed bitter tears before her son’s grave.
She has driven 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the tomb of Marine Infantry Sub-Official David Shane Spicer, who fell in battle in July.
No one should ever forget why we are free ... my son paid for it, she said.
“When I’ve been gone for a long time, I want someone to remember him.”
U.S. government contractors arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a U.S. government contractor who sold mobile phones and notebooks in the country, State Department officials said on Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company works on projects for clients, such as USAID, the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
U.S. consular officials in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5.
The special indictments have not yet been released, although under Cuban law a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything under the charge of "danger".
All so-called counter-revolutionary activities, including light protests and critical writings, carry a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered serious crimes.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who more often describes how she and her husband are being persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly asked for permission to leave the country to receive awards, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to heighten tensions between the Castro Brothers’ communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which had sought a “slow” approach to improving relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first reported Friday night by the New York Times.
The new U.S. policy emphasizes that the United States will provide a return if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as releasing political prisoners and creating more room for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and coveted products in a country where the average earnings of a government employee are $15 per month.
The Cuban government has only allowed normal citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year, they are mainly used to send text messages, as a 15-minute phone call would cost a day’s wages.
Internet use is extremely restricted on the island.
It is accessible in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government agencies, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
For many websites, access is restricted.
Arrest of an American is rare in Cuba.
Most of the few U.S. citizens who are in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokeswoman for the U.S. Department of State in Havana.
Berbena said she could not give any further information on the arrest.
Arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the delivery of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the "Human Rights Watch" group, which recently issued a harsh report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, the same Cuba, the landing of Fistro.
Vivanco said the defendants would very often be arrested, convicted and imprisoned within a day.
He said that any solution would likely be political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, especially at a time when both countries are moving towards each other for more dialogue.
Pakistani government reveals plan to send men to Afghanistan
Pakistani authorities uncovered on Saturday an allegedly leading head of a conspiracy aimed at sending five men from North Virginia to Afghanistan to kill U.S. soldiers, saying they hoped this case could help uncover an extensive network of terrorist recruiters who have radically turned off the Internet.
Investigators said they were looking for an opaque insurgent, known as Saifullah, who had invited the men to Pakistan after he tracked them down because one of them had commented on the terrorist attacks on the YouTube video site.
Saifullah became the leader of these men after their arrival in Pakistan and tried to help them reach the remote area in Pakistan’s tribal belt, which is home to Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a Pakistani intelligence official who was briefed on the matter said on Saturday that Saifullah was unable to convince the al-Qaeda leaders that the men were not part of a CIA conspiracy to undermine the terrorist network.
As a result, they were detained for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the inhospitable mountains in the northwest, which have become a haven for terrorists.
They were considered part of a covert operation.
That is why they were rejected, said the government official, who wanted to remain anonymous because of the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said the men were by no means discouraged and continued to try to get the right recommendations to gain access to the al-Qaida camps when they were arrested by Pakistani law enforcement authorities.
The case of the five men – who are still in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI – underscores the crucial role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and possibly more importantly, in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the September 11, 2001 attacks, the US intelligence has made it a matter of utmost urgency to house human asset posts within Al Qaeda.
The recruits of the organization act as gatekeepers who do not allow in those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who could be spies.
American recruits are undergoing a special examination by A Kaida, analysts said.
However, due to their potential access to U.S. targets and their propaganda value, they are also considered extremely attractive to the group.
Evan Kohlmann, senior analyst at the US-based NEFA Foundation, said terrorist groups have also become much more cautious about who they allow access to in recent years, as U.S. intelligence services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you try to include someone in these groups, what better way to go than to follow the recruitment model that so many have already followed?
The model is now much more based on the Internet.
Tens of thousands of protesters call for climate action in Copenhagen
Tens of thousands of protesters marched through the streets here on Saturday, demanding from the dealers in the city’s Bella Convention Center bolder action on climate protection.
Demonstrators said 100,000 people had joined the event, while police estimates were more likely to be around 25,000.
The event was relatively peaceful, although a handful of masked activists set fire to small explosives near some government buildings in downtown.
On a day when the UN-sponsored climate negotiations did little, thousands of activists wandered through the city with banners stating in English “There is no Planet B” and one in Spanish that declared “The Earth says “Enough”.
Some stars joined the protest, for example the Danish model, photographer Helena Christensen, who said that traveling to Peru, the birthplace of her mother, made her aware of the heartbreaking problems the country is struggling with due to the already tangible effects of climate change.
That’s part of the reason why I decided to take part in the big demonstration – to pass on the word and appeal to the world leaders to reach a fair, ambitious and binding agreement,” she said.
It is not an easy task, but it must be done now and there is no way around it.
Police prevented the protesters from getting too close to Bella Center, saying they had arrested 19 people, mainly because they were either masked or carrying pocket knives.
According to Danish law, these actions are prohibited during demonstrations.
According to one viewer, who did not want to be named because he was involved in the climate negotiations, masked demonstrators in black clothes set fire to several explosives near the Copenhagen main canal, near which several ministries are located.
They threw them near the buildings, he said, adding that they began as light rockets, but were then followed by "a few large explosions."
Inside the convention center, people gathered in front of television screens to watch the demonstration all afternoon.
But the protest has apparently not reached the consciousness of key officials, such as Su Wie, China’s chief climate dealer.
Asked if he thought the demonstration would have a constructive effect on international considerations, he replied in English: "This is something I was not aware of at all."
He then continued in Mandarin and said, "Because the venue is big, I can't hear what's going on outside."
He noted that it depends on the perspective of the individual whether the demonstration would harm or help.
It shows the concentration of the general public and various sectors on the issue of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "you can also say that they interfere with the negotiations or the freedom of other people."
Test data show stubborn breed air
The testimonies of math performance were welcome good news for public schools in Washington, D.C., last week.
Although Washington District is still far behind the country’s top performing schools, the testimonials show that the fourth and eighth graders have made faster progress over the past two years than cities that include Atlanta, Chicago, and New York.
But what is included in the latest figures of the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) is the persistent performance gap between African-American and white students, both locally and nationally.
The average score of white fourth graders from Washington D.C. rose from 262 to 270 in the last two years (on a scale of 500), but their African-American peers rose only three points from 209 to 212.
The performance gap actually increased from 53 to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of African-American eighth graders remained essentially the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white students was not included in the test data because the sample size was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth graders in 2003 when the first NAEP was detected in this district was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score reached by the children of both groups has grown over this time span, the difference has hardly decreased by now 58 points.
Some of the district’s education advocates expressed their concern last week that the results, celebrated by school chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic mayor Adrian M. Fenty, were largely driven by white students who are already high-performing children anyway.
This suggests that we have raised the overall score by treating those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and difficult, said Jeff Smith, a board member of D.C. Voice, a nonprofit group advocating for education equality in Washington D.C.
I’m not jumping up and down for a span of two or three points, said Democratic Washington City Councillor Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in the fourth grade of Eaton Elementary School.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee’s management style, said the message of the exam scores is that the city’s high schools urgently need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, I respect that.
What scares me, though, is that we don’t roughly spend the time and energy we need to spend on our high school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of the underperforming students.
This fall, for example, some teachers will be trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, that targets students in the upper grades of primary and secondary school who have not mastered basic reading skills at the beginning of their school career and who are significantly behind their peers.
Daily mathematics, a curriculum that focuses from kindergarten to sixth grade games and real-life experiences, was brought to Washington under former school supervisor Clifford Janey, and this curriculum is attributed to some of the NAEP progress reported last week.
I think we need to continue to work to bring the best measures to the benefit of students who are below the grade level, Rhee said.
Others say the NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the additional money and resources for the poor schools that are needed to narrow the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, professor of education at the University of California at Berkeley, who is investigating urban exam results.
The conventional remedy is to focus its resources and management reforms on the schools located in Washington, D.C.’s poorest areas.
The objective could have political repercussions that work against this important agenda item.
The weakness, of course, as with other urban school inspectors, is that she tries to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to ensure that we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighborhoods so that all families, regardless of where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public schooling.
Janey, who is now a school inspector in Newark, said this week in an interview that one of the most significant elements in closing the performance gap is to extend the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with charter schools.
One has to increase the school year to nearly 200 days to have the strength to change, said Janey, who came to an agreement with his teachers' union last year over 185 days a year, which he sees as "a milestone" on the way to a larger increase in the next contract.
Higher education for more people than prospects for the future
The bus reaches Gettysburg College with a loud whistle.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, comes out and blinks for a moment at the sight of the white columns, the brick facades and the emerald green lawn.
Graciela’s parents hardly finished high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was rescued in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never set foot on a college campus.
Her attitude and that of the other eighth graders of the group who explore Gettysburg, where tuition costs $38,690 a year, was more the one of an awe-inspiring visitor than the one of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes! I will be here soon!" said Graciela, who would like to study medicine when the guide announced that they had now entered the building for natural sciences.
"Wow, really?" she said thoughtfully when she was told of the school's low professor-to-student ratio.
The college in Pennsylvania was the 7th that the kids attended on their three-day tour and now they have fully embraced the intended message: The question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of children of Hispanic immigrants born in the U.S. who do not finish high school or become pregnant as teenagers, but on the other hand there are also hundreds of thousands who receive the college education necessary to rise to the middle class.
In fact, one in five of these “second generations” of Hispanic Americans graduates from college – a remarkable achievement as many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the United States without having completed high school.
Their success stories are important, researchers say, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country’s workforce.
Those who study powerful children say that they often have a natural affinity for school and a drive to success inherent in them.
Many of them also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counseling programs also play a big role by helping Graciela and millions of kids like her get to college, especially if these efforts persist for a long time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents do not have the experience and skills to help them find their way through the system, then a single measure at some point will not solve the problem either, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at the University of California in Davis who studied Hispanic American students.
We need to think about providing a support network for these children from preschool to high school.
The federal program that had funded Gracielas College tour is a useful example.
It’s known as GEAR UP – Turning One Gang Up – and provides more than $300 million a year for local school systems to start college preparation programs that begin when low-income students are in high school and continue until they finish high school.
According to the U.S. Department of Education, the program has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, more than 60% of whom have gone to college.
Iraqi Ministry of Oil signs contracts with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has been able to get major oil companies to rebuild their damaged infrastructure at two auctions closed on Saturday.
The 10 contracts signed by the Iraqi oil ministry with foreign oil companies suggest that China, Russia and European oil companies are ready to play an important role in renovating the Iraqi oil industry, which has been crippled for decades by war and economic sanctions.
U.S. companies were only able to book shares in two of the 10 auctioned fields.
Seven U.S. companies had paid to participate in the second auction, which began on Friday.
The only company that made a bid attracted the shorter one.
Two American companies were able to conclude contracts for fields auctioned in June.
The thinly planted representatives of American oil multis at the opening of the Iraqi oil industry surprised the analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors after 6 years of war, and instead of US companies, Asian and European are settling ahead, said Ruba Husari, the editor of Iraq Oil Forum, an online news service.
There will be no further offers in Iraq for a long time.
Security concerns underscored by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday and political instability from the U.S. military’s withdrawal have likely prevented U.S. oil companies from engaging more strongly in Iraq, which has the world’s third-largest proven crude reserves, analysts said.
U.S. firms have been disadvantaged in some cases because competitors, especially the Chinese and other state-controlled energy companies, have significantly lower wage costs and are more likely to take risks because they do not have to hold shareholders accountable.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies to be able to enter into contracts with the department.
Larger U.S. companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which maintain close ties with the Iraqi oil ministry and have been on the sidelines with technical advice in recent years, have gone empty.
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the main players in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The state-owned China National Petroleum Corporation has bid for more contracts than any other company and could go home with large packages of contracts for two larger fields.
We all know, said the spokesman for the oil ministry, Assam Jihad, that China is on its way to becoming one of the world’s largest economies as well as a technology power.
We are convinced that the Chinese company can measure itself with its counterparts and will fulfill its commitments to Iraq.
For bidding, pre-selected companies issued bids, which were then compared with the fee per barrel of oil, which the ministry was willing to pay to increase the output of each field beyond the current level.
Al Qaeda's top planner apparently killed in Pakistan
An apparent U.S. missile attack along the Pakistani border with Afghanistan is said to have killed a top al-Qaeda deployment planner this week, U.S. counter-terrorism officials reported on Friday.
This would be, if confirmed, the second deadly attack on a senior official of the terrorist organization this fall.
Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arabs who, according to U.S. sources and Pakistani officials in the region, were killed by a number of missiles that hit their vehicle on Tuesday near the city of Miran Shah in the northern province of Waziristan.
Local authorities reported that the missiles were fired by a type of drone deployed by the CIA in Pakistan’s lawless tribal belt.
They were driving in a white vehicle towards the Afghan border when the car was hit, a Pakistani civilian intelligence official from Miran Shah said by phone.
Local residents, suspected of belonging to the militants, ran to the scene and quickly seized all that was left of the "completely destroyed bodies".
Local authorities were unable to confirm the identities of the victims, but two U.S. counter-terrorism officials cited indefinite evidence that Somalia was among the dead.
Somalia was described as the leading military planner of Al Qaeda, which led operations of terrorist groups outside the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
He was involved in conspiracies around the world, noted a senior official who wanted to remain anonymous, and pointed to the delicate nature of U.S. airstrikes on Pakistani soil.
Assuming its central role as a given, this also included planning attacks against the United States and Europe.
He took strategic instructions from al-Qaida’s top leaders and implemented them into operational planning for possible terrorist attacks.
The second U.S. official said Somalia had quickly risen in the al-Qaeda hierarchy and had best links to other extremist groups in the region.
He may not be known to some Americans, the second official said, but this in no way diminishes the danger he posed to us and our allies.
If his death were confirmed, Somalia would be the second leading al Qaeda or Taliban leader to be killed since September when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant faction in the tribal area, and three other top activists.
The pace of attacks by CIA drones has dropped from an average of six operations per month to two since the summer, according to a summary of the Long War Journal, a nonprofit website.
The decline may be due to improved tactics by terrorist groups that have taken steps to reduce their vulnerability while brutally killing suspected informants, the site reported.
Leading UN envoy in Kabul to step down
U.N. envoy to Afghanistan Kai Eide said on Friday he would step down from office in March, ending a stormy term blurred by allegations of widespread corruption in the U.N.-backed Afghan presidential election.
His departure comes after the Obama administration decided to send another 30,000 U.S. soldiers to Afghanistan.
The U.N. envoy said he supports the troop increase, but he also expressed concerns that the U.S. military withdrawal schedule, which is set to begin in 18 months, could prompt other NATO governments to withdraw their forces.
We need to speed up the deployment of Afghan security forces and send the right signal to the Afghans that they can trust the international community, Eide said in a phone interview from Kabul.
Commitment must be long-term.
The Norwegian diplomat also urged the United States and other military powers to increase the number of international civilian aid workers to assist in the political transformation of Afghanistan.
The increase in troops on the military side must correspond to an increase on the civilian side, he said.
Eide said he would not resign, but would only fulfill an agreement made in March 2008 with his family to stay in Kabul for only two years.
He said he wanted the notification to the UN-
Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon is now forwarding so that he has time to arrange for a replacement.
What I’ve said is that he’s better off starting to look for a successor, Eide said.
When I came here, there was a two-month gap between my predecessor’s departure and my arrival.
Ban has started looking for a replacement, according to UN officials.
The UN representatives say he has considered the Swedish-Italian-born Staffan di Mistura, who recently led the UN mission in Baghdad and the Frenchman Jean-Marie Guéhenno, who previously led UN peacekeeping operations.
His position in Afghanistan was put to the test after his former deputy, Peter W. Galbraith, accused him in September of favoring President Hamid Karzai in the country’s presidential election and concealing evidence of massive electoral fraud.
Eide has denied all accusations, but he also said that Galbraith’s accusations – who was fired – “unquestionably hurt the mission because there was already a great deal of skepticism regarding international interference in the election.”
Eide said he had recommended the appointment of a leading civilian representative to coordinate the relief efforts of U.S.-led forces in Afghanistan.
He also urged the UN leadership to allow his successor to hire more personnel from the United States and other Western countries donating to the Afghan mission, saying that this would strengthen their confidence that their money will be properly spent.
Eide expressed his disappointment at the limitations of his forces in Afghanistan, saying that the cumbersome UN hiring arrangements have undermined his ability to bring in capable people.
The UN rules are designed so that since May, he said, I could only hire one person.
This is catastrophic and should not go on like this.
U.S. Defense Secretary Gates: Iran Must Expect Additional Sanctions
Defense Secretary Robert M. Gates said on Friday that world powers will soon impose "significant additional sanctions" on Iran because it has not participated in talks on its nuclear plans.
Gates spoke during a 7-day trip through the war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq to a group of about 300 U.S. soldiers in northern Iraq, downplaying the prospect of military action against the Islamic Republic of Iran.
There are no good options in Iran, he said in response to a soldier’s question about the likelihood of such a development.
“One of the things that is on my mind is if we have learned something from Iraq in the last six years, the war’s own unpredictability.”
The Obama administration is considering a package of sanctions targeting Iran’s military and political elite, but Gates has announced that some sanctions could also affect the average Iranian.
He said a “package of positive and negative incentives” is needed “to convince the Iranian government that it is actually less protected with nuclear weapons” because “your people will suffer tremendously” under the sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement from White House spokesman Robert Gibbs, the US government joined European top politicians in warning that Iran must expect "credible" consequences if it does not use its nuclear program to meet the demands of the UN Security Council and its International Atomic Energy Monitoring Organization.
Iran continues to argue that knowledge of nuclear technology should only be gained for peaceful purposes.
At talks in Geneva on October 1, Iran said it would resume talks on restricting its nuclear program and relinquish a substantial portion of its stockpile of enriched uranium in exchange for urgently needed nuclear fuel for its medical research reactor.
The U.S. government has pushed for this kind of agreement to build trust between the two parties and gain time for negotiations.
But Iran seems to have left the negotiations on the preliminary agreements since then -- in part, experts say, because the Iranian leadership is at odds about whether they should commit to the United States.
That Iran has simply left the international community alone with regard to some proposals it had already agreed to in early October has, frankly, brought the international community, including the Russians and Chinese, together in a way they never were in conjunction with important additional sanctions on Iran, Gates said.
President Obama has set Dec. 31 as a deadline for Iran to respond to these proposals before he continues to pursue other options, including those that former Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called “overwhelming sanctions.”
In a statement issued in New York, the Iranian mission to the United Nations condemned what it called on Thursday "unfounded and unfounded allegations" by some members of the Security Council about Iran's nuclear activities, saying they are ready to continue talks with the United States and five other world powers to "continue a long-term solution".
Gates, who was due to return to Washington on Friday, met with Iraqi Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki in the morning before flying to the oil-rich Kurdish region in Iraq to meet with the soldiers in Kirkuk and with Kurdish officials in Irbil.
Tensions between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq remain high, particularly in terms of borders, property rights and the distribution of public revenues.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the conflict potential to prevent delays in U.S. plans to reduce U.S. troop strength from 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
U.S. officials quoted Gates, who told Masud Barzani, president of the Kurdish regional government, “We will keep your security, your prosperity and your autonomy within a united Iraq.
We will not leave you.”
A change of pace in an ageing China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters that lectured them that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "One more baby means one more grave".
They learned these lessons so well that when government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change course this summer due to the low birth rate and the ageing population, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their answer was immediate and definitive: “Not at all.”
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
For a second child, nothing is left, said Wang, 31, a HR manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously fat, nurtured single children lovingly called “little emperors,” a population crisis is raging in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, according to the United Nations.
The Department of Population Affairs is firmly committed, while the number of people aged 60 and older is expected to rise explosively from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent by 2050, well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with a well-educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older made up nearly 22 percent of Shanghai’s reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of childbearing age need to have babies to “help reduce the ratio of ageing population shares and alleviate the shortage of workforce of the future.”
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Enshrined in the country’s constitution in 1978, China’s one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial provision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy face huge fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese state officials have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of the country’s natural resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many harsh slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Beijing University Institute of Population Research, said government officials recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with a partner who is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters instructing families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city administration has sent city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and shove information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not very encouraging, family planning representatives said.
Disappointing Reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said an upsurge is visible in the applications of couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, urban districts, on the other hand, report no change.
As an example, the municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the number of births in the city expected for 2010 despite the campaign will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of Shanghai’s Caolu municipality, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don’t want to have children anymore.
They want to give their first the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this is also legally allowed.
But, like many Chinese, they only have a small amount of government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we are being robbed of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not simply politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the HR manager, said she only wanted a child because she was also an single child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We’re not used to taking care of others, and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it unbridledly.
For middle-sized parents with double careers, through which the birth rate decreases, he said, it is about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of today’s 20- to 39-year-olds grew up watching their parents struggle during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don’t want such a life at all for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, poses huge demands on the time of parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the spatial question -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and the life plan -- "When the child is 9 months old, you have to have a resume ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to reach a higher standard of living, he said.
We don’t want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group Drafts Emissions Reduction Plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has again placed a focus on Friday with the publication of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with the industrial nations in the near future having the biggest burdens.
The text, which could provide the basis for a definitive political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has shown both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that will take time, as more than 100 top politicians from around the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for the key issues, including how industrialized and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit value of global temperature rise should be that policymakers would contribute.
The process is given a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN climate chief Yvo de Boer called “the big picture.”
It shows the outline of a possible agreement whereby, by 2020, industrialized nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also boosted talks on Friday by reassuring that it will provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change – from mastering floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday nonetheless brought the same verbal fireworks that the conversations of the past week had determined.
U.S. climate commissioner Todd Stern has rejected formulations demanding binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if they are not funded by industrialized nations.
This move announced that the Obama administration is moving a harder line with China than representatives of the Bush administration did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging countries rising up and taking action, Stern said, who also complained that the text was not going far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his statement an hour after the statement of Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei, who said that the leading American climate trader either lacked "reason" or it was "highly irresponsible" by him that he said earlier this week that the United States would not help China to finance the global.
Because the future economic direction of the world’s great powers is at stake, breaking lines have been opened both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging countries.
The current struggle relates to saving individual economies as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their respective commitments, while poorer countries claiming that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the major powers are struggling to determine who should bear the cost of braking greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to take more aggressive action to account for countries with very high greenhouse gas taxes for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic dominance will develop, according to Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the impacts of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States with 43 members submitted a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the offensive of the small island states “exerts political pressure on the entire political process,” partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging countries such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the open questions had to be clarified before the government leaders arrived to reach an agreement.
High-ranking officials, such as India’s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s Deputy Minister, flew off their planes and rushed through the hallways of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to stamp out claims that will be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people walk into and out of the congress center every day, guitar-playing activists hold nightly shows where they make fun of the countries they think they are betraying and selling, and drafts of contracts are hand-in-hand instead of e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: Almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday there will be 60 government leaders in Copenhagen.
We are coming to the upper league,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President of Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
