If it weren't for the pictures and the voices.
During the break, it may happen that a lazy boy with long, dark hair will respond to it.
If it answers him, the classmates look at it surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a sleepy daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn’t dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she asks herself sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other scams are not real and disappear again.
At night, the effects are usually scary.
Often the scams are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just introducing a new fellow student, while he explains mathematical equations to everyone else, both audible and visible at the table.
At night, the effects are usually frightening.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees are the cracks or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she yells at the figures.
She doesn’t tell her parents or friends anything about what they think she’s crazy about.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She passed high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art from despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from rice withdrawal, they are more likely to have hallucinations after a while, Kasten says.
I suspect the brain is then under-employed and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she calls Dad hasn’t been her bodily father since she can think.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same brain regions that process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between false images and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "haves its place in the brain, reality forms there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real.”
Even nighttime dream pictures value boxes as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their scams as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Limit state between dream and hallucination
In our too much-conscious world, imaginary experiences are unfortunately mostly pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, Professor in Heidelberg and Chief Physician of the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also carries positive, creative – madness is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-changed wakefulness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer believes to be real and that he cannot distinguish from the waking state even afterwards.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations related to trauma or illness, for example, in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by loss of self and world, such as persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A sort of boundary between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change is taking place, but the real situation is presented in the imagination.
An intense form of sense-foundation and sense-meaning in an intolerable situation, which allows us human beings to be able to shape ourselves, not to go into nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Change of Hearts" as a rescue of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, while his body is condemned to motionlessness in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immerses himself in a self-made world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot guards his health.
He lived in the early Middle Ages among nobles who made drugs from blood.
When a Greek man takes a motorcycle to his homeland, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He goes completely on in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are still very clear to me after years and in substantive details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug noise show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist summarizes, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
