75% of working mothers have problems at work due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and Women's Careers in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are big differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what kind of profession they perform.
Those of them who do no other work outside the home, only work half-days or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with fixed employment, especially in the public sector, shift the founding of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the 35-49 age group with a fixed employment will have their first child on average only 3.7 years after contracting, a number that increases to 4.1 years for women with a fixed employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have contracted their first child much later.
Moreover, the type of work also has a major impact on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of the readiness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of the women at the time of marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the level of education.
This difference could also be found in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between the ages of 35 and 49, depending on whether they only graduated from primary school or higher education, became mothers for the first time with an average of 25.1 or 32.1 each.
In addition, there is a further difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While women with a major degree are already getting married before their first fixed employment and have their first child, women with a middle or high school graduation are doing the exact opposite, first looking for a fixed employment and then getting married and then having their first child, Delgado notes.
