Sales of small trucks are rising again
After almost two years, the car market for small trucks is finally beginning to see some light at the end of the dark tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008, and, more importantly, they are the first ever increase after 22 consecutive months of steady decline, according to the figures presented by the Anfac and the Ganvam car dealerships.
However, these good figures are currently to be enjoyed only with great caution, since the reference data used for comparison are from November 2008, which was a particularly bad sales year with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
However, it must be borne in mind that, apart from last month’s increase, the total admissions for these 11 months are still 40% below the sales figures of the previous fiscal year.
Since January, a total of 95,853 vehicles have been sold, but this number includes all the vehicles that make up the small truck market: descendants of passenger cars, pick-ups, small trucks, small vans and lighter small trucks / trailers.
Furthermore, the same clouds of thunderstorms in the sky are still the ones that most undermine demand, because even if some of the vehicles are purchased by private individuals, the bulk of sales go to small and medium-sized enterprises, which in almost 100% of all cases make the purchase with a third-party financing.
For example, these constraints, which are the result of the credit institutions’ reversed monetary policy, must include additional factors such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
In this panorama, and unlike passenger cars, the financial support for the purchase of a 2000E vehicle has helped little.
However, this plan is not only for private individuals, even self-employed and small businesses have a right to it if they want to buy a small truck up to 3.5 tons with a CO2 emissions that cannot exceed 160 grams per mile driven, but the low sales figures speak for themselves.
