Assistance in braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now a duty
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time, and as is the case with the ESP stability control system at the moment, the braking assistance systems in emergency situations must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly licensed passenger cars and light trucks, for the rest of the vehicles a waiting period was set until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but due to its operation, these braking systems can also help to prevent many collisions.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking maneuver, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the braking force executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident before the collision were no longer able to step on the brake pedal and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, engages the braking system with maximum force and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, every year up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistants.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents with personal injury could be prevented - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while already exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver reacts, the system helps to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already unavoidable, the brake assistant applies maximum pressure to the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
